{
  "answer": "**Iqbal's poem \"Insaan\" (\"Man\" or \"Human Being\") appears as Chapter 14 in *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*.**[^1]\n\nIts central question revolves around the profound enigma of human existence: **Why has Creation made humanity an unsolved riddle, hidden from its own gaze—a restless seeker thirsting for self-knowledge amid a universe where everything else revels in its manifest purpose?** The poem contrasts humanity's unique isolation and bitterness (\"There is no one to share the sorrow of Man; How bitter is the existence of Man!\") with nature's harmonious fulfillment: waves surge to the sea, winds carry clouds, stars revel in fate, and the sun dutifully rises and sets.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 14 \"Insaan\" (translation). [Chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation-2.md/).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-4ea800](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation-2.md/#p-4ea800) to [p-d7ec8e](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation-2.md/#p-d7ec8e).\n\n[^3]: Ibid., [p-18d11b](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation-2.md/#p-18d11b)–[p-62d764](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation-2.md/#p-62d764).",
